04432nam a22005655i 9780774827591DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748275917 a10.1515/97807748275912doi  a(DE-B1597)661958  a(OCoLC)885913551  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE96.2b.G69 2014 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a371.829/970712231 aGoulet, Linda M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTeaching Each Other :bNehinuw Concepts and Indigenous Pedagogies /cKeith N. Goulet, Linda M. Goulet. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b17 b&w photographs, 2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tWhere We Are in Indigenous Education -- tWhere We’ve Been: Sociohistorical Realities -- tWhat to Build Upon: Sociocultural Strengths -- tHow to Get There: Conceptualizing Effective Teaching -- tWeechihitowin, Helping and Supporting Relationships: The Foundation -- tWeetutoskemitowin, Working Together: Social Systems -- tIseechigehina, Planned Actions: Connection to the Process -- tWeechiseechigemitowin, Strategic Alliances: Connection to the Content -- tBreaking Trail: Stories Outside the (Classroom) Box -- tIninee mamitoneneetumowin, Indigenous Thinking: Emerging Theory of Indigenous Education -- tAppendix 1: Cree Orthographic Chart -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades, educators have been seeking ways to improve outcomes for Indigenous students. Yet most Indigenous education still takes place within a theoretical framework based in Eurocentric thought. In Teaching Each Other, Linda Goulet and Keith Goulet provide an alternative framework for teachers working with Indigenous students – one that moves beyond acknowledging Indigenous culture to one that actually strengthens Indigenous identity. Drawing on Nehinuw (Cree) concepts such as kiskinaumatowin, or “teaching each other,” Goulet and Goulet provide a new approach to teaching Indigenous students. Kiskinaumatowin transforms the normally hierarchical teacher-student relationship by making students and teachers equitable partners in education. Enriched with the success stories of educators who are applying Nehinuw concepts in Saskatchewan, Canada, this book demonstrates how this framework works in practice. The result is an alternative teaching model that can be used by teachers anywhere who want to engage with students whose culture may be different from the mainstream.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree IndiansxEducationzCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aGoulet, Keith N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077482759140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774827591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774827591/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-141999-2  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles